# Literature Review: Consolidating Cybersecurity in Europe: A Case Study on Job Profiles Assessment

## Introduction

In the field of cybersecurity, it is crucial to educate and train professionals with the specific skills and
competencies required to address the evolving challenges in the digital landscape. This literature review
aims to explore the existing research findings related to job profiles assessment and the consolidation of
cybersecurity in Europe. By synthesizing the available literature, this review will provide insights into
the educational needs and assessment frameworks for cybersecurity professionals. Additionally, it will
identify knowledge gaps and suggest potential future research directions.

## Research Findings

### Implementing an Entrustable Professional Activities Framework in Undergraduate Medical Education: Early Lessons From the AAMC Core Entrustable Professional Activities for Entering Residency

Pilot
Lomis et al. (2017) discuss the implementation of an Entrustable Professional Activities (EPA) framework
in medical education. The study emphasizes the shift from time-based learning to outcome-based learning
and highlights the importance of assessing learners' readiness to perform specific professional activities.
Although this study focuses on medical education, it provides insights into the use of EPA frameworks
for assessing professionals' competencies in a specific domain.

### National Initiative for Cybersecurity Education (NICE) Cybersecurity Workforce Framework

The National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) developed the NICE Cybersecurity Workforce
Framework (2017) to provide a common language for describing and categorizing cybersecurity work
roles. This framework defines a set of knowledge, skills, and abilities (KSAs) required for various
cybersecurity job roles. While this framework is not specific to Europe, it offers a comprehensive
framework that can be adapted and utilized for consolidating cybersecurity job profiles assessment in
Europe.

### Constructing a Validity Argument for the Objective Structured Assessment of Technical Skills

(OSATS): A Systematic Review of Validity Evidence
Hatala et al. (2015) conducted a systematic review to construct a validity argument for the Objective
Structured Assessment of Technical Skills (OSATS) in medical education. The study highlights the
importance of establishing the validity of assessment methods, including the assessment of technical
