skills. This finding emphasizes the need for valid and reliable assessment frameworks in cybersecurity
job profiles assessment.

### Entrustable Professional Activities in Healthcare Education: A Scoping Review

Shorey et al. (2019) conducted a scoping review to explore the use of Entrustable Professional Activities
(EPAs) in healthcare education. The study provides insights into the application of EPAs as a framework
for assessing and entrusting learners with professional activities. While this study focuses on healthcare
education, it offers valuable insights that can be applied to the assessment of cybersecurity professionals'
competencies and job profiles.

### The Future Cybersecurity Workforce: Going Beyond Technical Skills for Successful Cyber Performance

Dawson and Thomson (2018) argue that successful performance in cybersecurity requires more than just
technical skills. The study highlights the importance of non-technical skills, such as communication,
problem-solving, and ethical decision-making, in cybersecurity professionals. This finding suggests the
need to consider a holistic approach to job profiles assessment in cybersecurity, encompassing both
technical and non-technical skills.

### Workforce Framework for Cybersecurity (NICE Framework)

The NIST Workforce Framework for Cybersecurity (2020) provides a comprehensive set of knowledge,
skills, and abilities (KSAs) required for cybersecurity professionals. This framework categorizes cybersecurity work roles and defines the KSAs associated with each role. While this framework is not
specific to Europe, it offers a valuable resource for developing a standardized framework for consolidating
cybersecurity job profiles assessment.

### Influence of Human Factors on Cyber Security within Healthcare Organizations: A Systematic

Review
Nifakos et al. (2021) conducted a systematic review to explore the influence of human factors on
cybersecurity within healthcare organizations. The study highlights the importance of considering human
factors, such as user behavior and organizational culture, in cybersecurity assessments. This finding
suggests the need to incorporate human factors assessment into the job profiles assessment framework
for cybersecurity professionals.

### Expert Assessment of the Top Platform Independent Cybersecurity Skills for Non-IT Professionals

Carlton and Levy (2015) conducted an expert assessment to identify the top platform-independent
cybersecurity skills for non-IT professionals. The study highlights the importance of assessing and
developing cybersecurity skills among professionals from diverse backgrounds. This finding suggests the
